                .-,------------X                                             X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| RASH is a contemporary story of modern urban Australia   X
                |#| and artists making it a living host for illegal artwork  X
                |#| called ‘street art’. This film explores the cultural     X
                |#| value of unsanctioned public art, and graffiti’s         X
                |#| contribution to a very public dialogue.                  X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| Rash, written RASH, is a 2005 Australian documentary     X
                |#| film, directed by Nicholas Hansen.                       X
                |#| Its subject is contemporary urban Australia and the      X
                |#| artists who are making it a host for illegal street art. X
                |#| With the tagline 'Scratch it and it spreads', Rash       X
                |#| explores the cultural value of unsanctioned public art   X
                |#| and the ways that street art and graffiti contribute to  X
                |#| public dialogue.                                         X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| Directed by Nicholas Hansen and Mutiny Media, Rash was   X
                |#| three years in the making and includes interviews with   X
                |#| many of Melbourne's inspired street art and graffiti     X
                |#| artists as well as visitors who came to Melbourne and    X
                |#| leave their mark. Rash is the first feature-length       X
                |#| documentary in Australia to focus on the new art form    X
                |#| of street art.                                           X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| Filming began in 2002 on this documentary, which conveys X
                |#| the commitment, ideals and beliefs demonstrated in       X
                |#| Melbourne street art. Artists use a variety of           X
                |#| approaches including bill posters, stencils, and         X
                |#| performance art put the artwork right in the public eye. X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| The film was made in the lead up to the Melbourne 2006   X
                |#| Commonwealth Games. Before the games local councils were X
                |#| juggling the need to present a clean and safe city for   X
                |#| visitors against the enthusiastic activities of street   X
                |#| and graffiti artists. A similar response was later       X
                |#| observed in the lead up to the London 2012 Summer        X
                |#| Olympics.                                                X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| In Rash the spirit of rebellion is channeled into street X
                |#| art and the visual conversations are spread across the   X
                |#| walls of Melbourne. Rash offers a rare look inside these X
                |#| graffiti artists world-view.                             X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| The musical soundtrack was created by Ryan Ritchie and   X
                |#| band True Live. The band was made up of MC Rhyno,        X
                |#| Thomas Butt (double bass), Tamil Rogeon (violin),        X
                |#| Tim Blake (cello), Ivan Khatchoyan (drums) and           X
                |#| Thai Mattus (keys).                                      X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| A 2006 review stated 'It is this rare spotlight on this  X
                |#| hidden subculture that makes Rash so fascinating and     X
                |#| potentially illuminating to those who view graffiti      X
                |#| artists as merely vandals. In fact, it is this           X
                |#| misconception of the graffiti artist and their role in   X
                |#| society that Hansen's film centrally explores.           X
                |#| Rash reveals that Melbourne's graffiti subculture is     X
                |#| not only a very tight knit community where everyone      X
                |#| knows what each other is doing. It is also governed by   X
                |#| a set of 'street etiquette'                              X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#| Prior to its 2006 TV broadcast in Australia              X
                |#| Sacha Molitorisz of The Age newspaper reviewed the film  X
                |#| saying 'This fresh documentary explores Melbourne's      X
                |#| flourishing graffiti subculture.'[3] Other notable       X
                |#| screenings include the 17 August 2008 event of           X
                |#| documentaries programmed in the 'Street Art'             X
                |#| exhibition at the Tate Modern in London.                 X
                |#| Archival footage from Rash was licensed to Banksy's      X
                |#| film production company Paranoid Pictures for the        X
                |#| opening montage of documentary Exit Through the          X
                |#| Gift Shop (2010).                                        X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#|                                                          X
                |#|                Shoutouts to our original group members,  X
                |#|                We'r still sneakin' around since 23years  X
